          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# James's Return-to-Running Plan\n\nWelcome back, James. First — five years of running and you've navigated a runner's knee recovery before and come back from it. That history matters. It tells me you know how to be patient with a body that needs time, and that you *do* come back. This plan is built to honor that.\n\nLet me walk you through what I've built for you, and why.\n\n---\n\n## The Big Picture: What We're Working With\n\nYour physiotherapist has cleared you for up to 20 minutes of easy running, with walking breaks if there's any foot discomfort. That's our absolute ceiling right now — not a suggestion, a boundary. Everything in this plan lives within it.\n\nYour pre-injury pace-zone index sits at 46.5, which gives us solid reference points, but here's the honest reality: after time off with an active plantar fasciitis, your current fitness is almost certainly a step below that benchmark. **That's completely normal and completely reversible.** We're not starting where you left off — we're starting where you *are*, and building from there with intention.\n\nThe goal for the next 8 weeks isn't performance. It's **tissue tolerance, consistency, and confidence.** Those three things are the foundation everything else gets built on.\n\n---\n\n## Your Training Paces\n\nAll paces come from your Daniels-Gilbert zones, anchored to your 44:00 10K. For this plan, **we're using only the easy pace range: 5:25–6:12 /km.** Toward the conservative end (5:50–6:12) is your friend right now — your foot will thank you for not pushing the bottom of that range.\n\nNo threshold, interval, or repetition work until your physio gives the green light. That's not a detour — it's the direct route back.\n\n---\n\n## How the Plan Is Structured\n\n**3 days per week** — consistent with your preference and appropriate for load management with an active injury.\n\n**Run/walk format** — we use walking breaks proactively, not just reactively. Walking isn't a sign of weakness; it's how we control impact load on healing tissue.\n\n**10% weekly volume cap** — we will not exceed 10% volume increase week over week. Your recent history (2.4 km → 8.5 km → 6.1 km) shows some natural fluctuation, so we're anchoring to a conservative starting point and building deliberately.\n\n**Deload every 4th week** — volume drops ~20% to let your body absorb the training and your foot to recover from cumulative load.\n\n---\n\n## The 8-Week Plan\n\n### Weeks 1–2 — Re-establishing the Habit\n*Focus: Consistency over distance. Walk/run format. Feel out your foot.*\n\n| Week | Day | Session | Format | Target Distance |\n|------|-----|---------|--------|----------------|\n| **1** | Tue | Easy run/walk | 8 min easy / 2 min walk × 2 | ~2.5 km |\n| | Thu | Easy run/walk | 8 min easy / 2 min walk × 2 | ~2.5 km |\n| | Sat | Easy run/walk | 8 min easy / 2 min walk × 2 | ~2.5 km |\n| **2** | Tue | Easy run/walk | 9 min easy / 1 min walk × 2 | ~2.8 km |\n| | Thu | Easy run/walk | 9 min easy / 1 min walk × 2 | ~2.8 km |\n| | Sat | Easy run/walk | 9 min easy / 1 min walk × 2 | ~2.8 km |\n\n*Week 1 total: ~7.5 km | Week 2 total: ~8.4 km*\n\n> **Coaching note:** If your foot speaks up at any point — not just pain, but tightness, pulling, or that familiar early warning feeling — take the walk break immediately. You don't have to wait for pain. Proactive management is smarter than reactive management.\n\n---\n\n### Week 3 — Pushing Gently Toward 20 Minutes\n*Focus: Extend the continuous running window.*\n\n| Day | Session | Format | Target Distance |\n|-----|---------|--------|----------------|\n| Tue | Easy run/walk | 12 min easy / 2 min walk / 5 min easy | ~3.0 km |\n| Thu | Easy run/walk | 12 min easy / 2 min walk / 5 min easy | ~3.0 km |\n| Sat | Easy run/walk | 14 min easy / 2 min walk / 4 min easy | ~3.2 km |\n\n*Week 3 total: ~9.2 km*\n\n---\n\n### Week 4 — Deload \uD83D\uDD04\n*Reduce volume ~20%. Let the body consolidate gains.*\n\n| Day | Session | Format | Target Distance |\n|-----|---------|--------|----------------|\n| Tue | Easy run/walk | 10 min easy / 2 min walk / 5 min easy | ~2.5 km |\n| Thu | Easy run/walk | 10 min easy / 2 min walk / 5 min easy | ~2.5 km |\n| Sat | Easy run/walk | 12 min easy / 2 min walk / 3 min easy | ~2.7 km |\n\n*Week 4 total: ~7.7 km*\n\n> **Coaching note:** Deload weeks can feel frustrating when things are going well — like you're leaving fitness on the table. You're not. You're making the following three weeks possible.\n\n---\n\n### Weeks 5–6 — Building Toward Continuous 20 Minutes\n*Focus: Reduce walk breaks. Increase total volume cautiously.*\n\n| Week | Day | Session | Format | Target Distance |\n|------|-----|---------|--------|----------------|\n| **5** | Tue | Easy run | 18 min easy (walk break if needed) | ~3.0 km |\n| | Thu | Easy run | 18 min easy (walk break if needed) | ~3.0 km |\n| | Sat | Easy run | 20 min easy (walk break if needed) | ~3.4 km |\n| **6** | Tue | Easy run | 20 min easy | ~3.4 km |\n| | Thu | Easy run | 20 min easy | ~3.4 km |\n| | Sat | Easy run | 20 min easy | ~3.4 km |\n\n*Week 5 total: ~9.4 km | Week 6 total: ~10.2 km*\n\n> By Week 6, the goal is three comfortable 20-minute runs. Not fast — comfortable. If Week 6 feels genuinely easy, that's the signal that your body is adapting well.\n\n---\n\n### Week 7 — Deload \uD83D\uDD04\n*Protect the gains. Don't rush the exit.*\n\n| Day | Session | Format | Target Distance |\n|-----|---------|--------|----------------|\n| Tue | Easy run | 15 min easy | ~2.5 km |\n| Thu | Easy run | 15 min easy | ~2.5 km |\n| Sat | Easy run | 18 min easy | ~3.0 km |\n\n*Week 7 total: ~8.0 km*\n\n---\n\n### Week 8 — Reassessment Week\n*Focus: How does your foot feel? What does your physio say?*\n\n| Day | Session | Format | Target Distance |\n|-----|---------|--------|----------------|\n| Tue | Easy run | 20 min easy | ~3.4 km |\n| Thu | Easy run | 20 min easy | ~3.4 km |\n| Sat | Easy run | 20 min easy | ~3.4 km |\n\n*Week 8 total: ~10.2 km*\n\n> **Week 8 is a checkpoint, not an ending.** This is the week to return to your physiotherapist and report honestly on how the foot has responded. Their answer shapes everything that comes next — duration increases, a return to longer runs, and eventually (when cleared) a structured reintroduction of quality work.\n\n---\n\n## What Comes After Week 8 (The Trajectory Forward)\n\nOnce your physio clears you for more than 20 minutes:\n\n1. **Weeks 9–12:** Extend long run on Saturdays by 5 minutes every 2 weeks. Keep weekday runs at 20–25 min.\n2. **Weeks 13–16:** Begin building toward 30–35 min runs. Total weekly volume approaches 15–18 km.\n3. **When fully cleared for speed work:** Reintroduce easy strides first (not intervals), then threshold work — all anchored to your Daniels-Gilbert zones.\n4. **Return-to-racing:** With consistent training, a sub-44:00 10K is well within reach. Your fitness base doesn't disappear — it waits.\n\n---\n\n## Daily Routine Reminders\n\nThese sit outside my scope as a coach, but they're worth flagging so you can discuss with your physio:\n\n- **Morning foot stiffness** after sleep or sitting is a common plantar fasciitis signal — worth noting in a simple training log before runs\n- **Footwear** matters here more than most injury contexts — your physio is the right person to advise on this\n- **Post-run foot care** — ask your physio what they recommend for your specific protocol\n\n---\n\n## One Last Thing\n\nYou've done this before — you came back from runner's knee, and you're five years into this sport. This injury is a chapter, not the conclusion. The discipline you're showing right now, keeping sessions short and honest, is *exactly* the work that makes the next phase possible.\n\nWhat questions do you have about the plan? And is there anything about Week 1 specifically that feels uncertain — whether that's the format, the paces, or just how your foot is responding day to day?"
        }
